content:
Thinking a bit more on this, is it necessary to have a human readable `proof_type` encoding?

From the perspective of a zkAttestor, what they need to know seems to be only a allow list of `zkvm_guest` of current fork, for instance:

```json
[
  {
    "zkvm_kind": "zisk",
    "zkvm_version": "v0.16.1",
    "program_vk": "0x01....ef" // the only thing the <zkvm_kind>@<zkvm_version> verifier needs to verify a proof
  },
  {
    // ...
  }
]
```

And the proof gossiped can be attached with the `zkvm_guest_id = hash(zkvm_kind || zkvm_version || program_vk)` so zkAttestor knows which `zkvm_guest` verifier to use (it doesn't even need to know about EL kind if all guests support canonical input/output). And for each fork we only need to bump this list.

For CL requesting zkboost for proofs (I guess this usecase only needed in testnet), assuming the CL and zkboost have the same list, the zkboost proof request API can just accept the index to the list to know which `zkvm_guest` to prove (and similarly for spining up a CL that does proof request, we pass the indices we want)

Not sure if it makes sense or not, just thinking out loud here.
